Pactolus – Project Overview
Product Purpose

Pactolus is a versioned analytical workflow system for reinsurance teams.

Insurance and reinsurance companies frequently export large spreadsheets of claims and policy data from internal systems. These datasets are messy, inconsistent, and change over time. Analysts then perform complex analysis in spreadsheets to reconcile datasets, validate numbers, and compute financial summaries.

The problem is that spreadsheet workflows are:

fragile

difficult to reproduce

opaque

prone to silent errors

impossible to audit reliably

Pactolus solves this by turning spreadsheet-based workflows into a structured, versioned, and inspectable analytical system.

The system:

ingests messy datasets

standardizes them using mapping

records every transformation step

allows analysts to explore assumptions safely

makes every result reproducible and traceable

Pactolus should feel conceptually similar to:

Git for analytical workflows

CAD feature history for data analysis

Cursor-style step history for analytics

The goal is controlled flexibility: analysts can explore and modify assumptions while the system preserves a deterministic record of how results were produced.

Core System Principles
1. Deterministic Core

All canonical data transformations and calculations must be deterministic.

AI may assist users by proposing mappings or analysis suggestions, but AI must never directly modify canonical data.

Every transformation must be:

explicit

validated

reproducible

2. Raw Data Preservation

All uploaded data must first be stored losslessly.

Raw rows from uploaded CSV files are stored as JSON records so that:

original data is never lost

mappings can be re-run

debugging is possible

outputs can always be traced to source rows

Canonical datasets are derived from raw rows.

3. Claims and Policies Are Separate Datasets

Reinsurance workflows involve two major dataset types:

Claims

Individual claim-level records.

Typical fields include:

claim_number

accident_date

policy_number

paid amounts

outstanding reserves

incurred totals

Policies

Policy-level records describing insurance contracts.

Typical fields include:

policy_number

insured_name

effective_date

expiration_date

premium values

line_of_business

These datasets:

arrive in separate CSV exports

have different column structures

are uploaded independently

However, they can belong to the same snapshot.

4. Snapshot Model

A Snapshot represents a point-in-time extract of company data.

A snapshot may include:

a Claims dataset

a Policies dataset

Each dataset is ingested separately but linked by snapshot_id.

Snapshots are immutable once ingestion completes.

5. Raw → Canonical Data Model

The system uses a two-layer ingestion architecture.

Raw Layer

Uploaded CSV rows are stored as raw JSON records.

This preserves original source data.

Canonical Layer

Raw rows are mapped into canonical schemas for:

claims

policies

Canonical schemas contain only fields required for downstream analysis.

Additional unmapped data can remain in raw JSON or an extras_json column.

6. AI-Assisted Column Mapping

CSV exports from different companies use inconsistent column names.

Example:

"Claim Number"

"Claim No."

"Occurrence ID"

These may all represent the same canonical field.

Pactolus uses AI to propose mappings between source columns and canonical fields.

However:

AI output must be validated before use

mappings must pass schema validation

mappings must succeed on sample rows

users may edit or approve mappings

AI is advisory only.

All canonical data must be generated through validated transformations.

7. Analytical Runs

All analysis occurs within Runs.

A run represents a complete analytical workflow executed on a snapshot.

Runs record:

dataset inputs

mappings

filters

assumptions

calculations

outputs

Runs allow users to experiment with different assumptions while preserving reproducibility.

8. Run Step History

Every analytical action must be recorded as a Run Step.

Examples of step types:

dataset upload

mapping application

mapping edits

canonicalization

filtering

grouping

metric definition

reconciliation

aggregation

AI suggestions

user acceptance of suggestions

Each step records:

step type

parameters

actor (user, AI, or system)

timestamp

optional output references

Steps are immutable.

9. Branching and Forking Runs

Users must be able to fork runs to explore alternate assumptions.

Example:

Run A:

upload dataset

apply mapping

define expense calculation

compute aggregates

User may create Run B from Run A:

Run B:
5. modify expense definition
6. recompute aggregates

Both analytical paths are preserved.

This enables safe experimentation and comparison.

10. Reproducible Execution

Runs must be replayable.

The system should be able to reproduce outputs by executing steps sequentially from the start of a run.

This ensures results are deterministic and auditable.

Initial Feature Scope

Current development focus is:

CSV ingestion

Raw row storage

AI-assisted mapping

Canonical data extraction

Run and run step recording

Branchable analytical runs

Advanced analytics, reconciliation engines, and actuarial calculations will be added later.

Technology Stack

Backend: Node.js

API: Express + tRPC

Validation: Zod

ORM: Drizzle

Database: PostgreSQL

Workflow engine: Temporal

Testing: Vitest

Frontend: Next.js

Design Goals

Code should prioritize:

clarity

determinism

explicit transformations

traceability of outputs

modular design

Avoid hidden transformations or implicit assumptions.

Every important action in the system should be observable and reproducible.

